unhappy;
and
that
it
should
be
through
her
means
that
she,
his
favourite
child,
should
be
distressing
him
by
her
choice,
should
be
filling
him
with
fears
and
regrets
in
disposing
of
her
was
a
wretched
reflection,
and
she
sat
in
misery
till
Mr.
Darcy
appeared
again,
when,
looking
at
him,
she
was
a
little
relieved
by
his
smile.
In
a
few
minutes
he
approached
the
table
where
she
was
sitting
with
Kitty;
and,
while
pretending
to
admire
her
work
said
in
a
